WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.340
So, the task was, Vinay asked me, again, thanks for the kind invitation, Vinay asked me to talk, really address this question as to whether the BTK degraders really are just another BTK targeted therapy, or are we really overcoming resistant to BTK kinase inhibitors?

00:00:20.340 --> 00:00:39.480
And I think everybody in this audience is familiar, and we've had a number of discussions in regards to BTK degraders. These are molecules that essentially lead to BTK block by mediating BTK degradation through the proteasome pathway.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:49.460
They disrupt both the catalytic activity of BTK and also the scaffolding function, and that's consequently what's leading to actual cell death.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:07.420
They don't require sustained target binding as a single molecule, as a single molecule can degrade multiple BTK molecules, and then there's broad mutation coverage, which we'll cover, and there's variable CNS penetration between the two compounds.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:19.420
So, there's some overlap with some of the talks here, so I will concentrate specifically on the question of overcoming resistance. This is data from BGB 16673.

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:48.240
This is data from BGB 16673, the BTK degrader from B1. This was the Cadence 101 study, and I'll highlight here, this is a high-risk patient population as enumerated in the red blocks on the left bottom here, but on the right side, you can see this is actually a fairly heavily pre-treated patient population for the entire lines of therapy, and 90% of the patients had covalent BTK inhibitor, 20% non-covalent.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:54.440
24% of the patients were double exposed, and 17% of the patients were triple exposed.

00:01:54.440 --> 00:02:13.660
Now, on the bottom right-hand side, 90%, almost 90%, 89.1% of the patients were labeled as, yeah, were discontinued in prior BTK inhibitor due to progressive disease on the BTK inhibitor, at least a large portion of the patient population, thank God.

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:18.980
A large portion of the patient population.

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:26.640
The population actually was indeed, you could say, refractory to BTK inhibitors.

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:41.380
This is a very well-tolerated regimen with not a lot of significant adverse events, really some pneumonia and neutropenia, which I think one of my colleagues will cover.

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:48.640
Having said that, it is a very active strategy in terms of disease control, so rapid improvement in...

00:02:48.640 --> 00:03:00.380
Platelet counts, rapid improvement in neutrophil counts, median time to response is within the first two cycles of therapy, so within two months, the patients actually have improvement.

00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:02.880
And then I'll highlight the data here.

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:12.800
The overall response rate in the red box here highlighted is 94% in this heavily pre-treated patient population with rapid responses.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:18.300
Most of the responses tend to be partial response or partial response with lymphocytosis.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:37.820
And looking at, again, across various high-risk categories, double-exposed, 93% responses, triple-exposed, 75% responses, and even in the high-risk molecular categories, you can see substantially higher responses there.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:40.640
Are the responses durable?

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:41.820
Indeed, that's what you can see.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:46.420
At 18 months, the progression-free survival here is 65%.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:46.900
So not only the response rate is higher, but the progression-free survival here is also higher.

